### Abstract Classes

Abstract classes cannot be instantiated directly. They define a common interface and may have abstract methods (without implementation).

```dart
abstract class Animal {
  void makeSound(); // Abstract method (no body)

  void eat() {
    print('Animal is eating'); // Concrete method
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  @override
  void makeSound() {
    print('Woof!');
  }
}

void main() {
  var dog = Dog();
  dog.makeSound(); // Woof!
  dog.eat();       // Animal is eating

  // var animal = Animal(); // ERROR: Cannot instantiate abstract class
}
```

### Abstract Methods

Abstract methods are declared without a body. They must be implemented by non-abstract subclasses.

```dart
abstract class Shape {
  double area();      // Abstract
  double perimeter(); // Abstract

  String describe() => 'Shape with area: ${area()}'; // Concrete
}

class Circle extends Shape {
  double radius;

  Circle(this.radius);

  @override
  double area() => 3.14159 * radius * radius;

  @override
  double perimeter() => 2 * 3.14159 * radius;
}
```

### Abstract Classes with Fields

```dart
abstract class Database {
  String host;

  Database(this.host);

  void connect();
  void disconnect();
  Future<List<Map<String, dynamic>>> query(String sql);
}

class PostgresDatabase extends Database {
  PostgresDatabase(String host) : super(host);

  @override
  void connect() => print('Connected to Postgres at $host');

  @override
  void disconnect() => print('Disconnected');

  @override
  Future<List<Map<String, dynamic>>> query(String sql) async {
    print('Executing: $sql');
    return [];
  }
}
```

### Abstract vs Concrete

| Feature | Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|---------|---------------|----------------|
| Instantiation | Cannot instantiate | Can instantiate |
| Abstract methods | Can have them | Cannot have them |
| Constructors | Can have constructors | Can have constructors |
| Fields | Can have fields | Can have fields |

> **Key Point:** Use abstract classes to define contracts with shared implementation. Abstract methods force subclasses to provide specific behavior while allowing shared concrete methods.

codeExample:
abstract class PaymentProcessor {
  void authorize(double amount);
  void capture(double amount);
  void refund(double amount);

  void processPayment(double amount) {
    authorize(amount);
    capture(amount);
    print('Payment of \$${amount} processed');
  }
}

class StripeProcessor extends PaymentProcessor {
  @override
  void authorize(double amount) => print('Stripe: Authorized \$$amount');

  @override
  void capture(double amount) => print('Stripe: Captured \$$amount');

  @override
  void refund(double amount) => print('Stripe: Refunded \$$amount');
}

void main() {
  var processor = StripeProcessor();
  processor.processPayment(100.0);
  processor.refund(25.0);
}
